## v1.4.0 (2026-06-14)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus /myrmidon-swarm driving a stack of PRs to merge, 2026-06-14
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Expanded `description` triggers to (9) arming auto-merge on a STACKED PR — retarget to main
  BEFORE arming or it squash-merges into the intermediate base and can ORPHAN the change; and
  (10) recovering an orphaned stacked merge via cherry-pick onto a fresh main branch.
- Added Phase 3d "NEVER Arm Auto-Merge on a Still-Stacked PR — It Merges Into the Intermediate
  Base and Can ORPHAN the Change" — the hazard (GitHub fires the merge against the intermediate
  base the moment it's eligible), the critical retargeting-timing facts (auto-retarget only on
  base MERGE, not on base CLOSE; `gh pr edit --base main` fails once merged into a closed base),
  the prevention sequence (confirm base content on main → `gh pr edit --base main` → rebase onto
  main → arm last), the orphan-detection + cherry-pick recovery (`git cherry-pick -S`), and the
  fan-out prevention (close no-op base, retarget+rebase all dependents to main, arm last).
- Added a When-to-Use bullet for arming auto-merge on a stacked PR (retarget first).
- Added 2 Failed Attempts rows: arming auto-merge on a still-stacked PR (orphaned the change into
  a closed intermediate base); assuming GitHub auto-retargets a stacked PR to main when its base
  CLOSES (it only does so when the base MERGES).
- Added a prose cross-link ("see also") to `github-auto-merge-ci-gating-merge-method` (the
  arming/gating companion) and `pr-rebase-conflict-resolution-patterns` (the rebase silent-drop /
  superseded-PR detection used to find no-op bases). Those skills are NOT amended.
- Added Verified On row for the ProjectHephaestus 2026-06-14 stacked-PR auto-merge session
  (RC2 orphaned + recovered, RC6 folded harmlessly).
- Bumped version 1.3.0 -> 1.4.0 (minor — new phase/sections/failures, no breaking changes).
- Updated `date` to 2026-06-14.

NOTE: The skill's frontmatter `verification` field remains `verified-ci` (it reflects the
prior CI-verified body). The v1.4.0 additions in this entry are **verified-local** — observed
this session in ProjectHephaestus but not yet independently CI-confirmed. New sections are
marked `(v1.4.0, verified-local)` inline so the new material is not overclaimed as verified-ci.

### Why

While a /myrmidon-swarm drove a stack of PRs to merge in ProjectHephaestus, a stacked-PR
auto-merge hazard surfaced that prior versions did not cover:

1. **Arming auto-merge on a still-stacked PR merges it into the intermediate base, not main —
   and can orphan the change.** When a PR's base is another open/feature branch and you arm
   `gh pr merge --auto --squash`, GitHub fires the merge against that INTERMEDIATE base the
   moment it's eligible. Two PRs (RC2, RC6) were armed while still based on intermediate
   branches. RC6 was harmless (its base was another open PR that itself merges to main, so RC6
   folded into it). RC2's base (`chore-ruff-format-drift`) belonged to a CLOSED PR — so RC2's
   change merged onto a dead branch and was ORPHANED from main (PR showed `state=MERGED` but the
   content was on a branch that never reaches main).

2. **GitHub does NOT auto-retarget a stacked PR to main until its base PR actually MERGES.** If
   the base is CLOSED (not merged), the dependent is stranded, and once it has merged into the
   dead base `gh pr edit --base main` fails with "Cannot change the base branch of a closed pull
   request". Lesson: before arming a stacked PR, retarget it to `main` first and only after the
   base content is already on main; never arm a PR whose base you intend to close/abandon. For a
   fan-out where a base becomes a no-op (content already merged via a sibling — confirmed via a
   rebase that silently drops it as "patch contents already upstream"), close that base PR,
   retarget+rebase all dependents to main, and arm last.

3. **Recovery for an orphaned stacked merge:** detect with `gh pr view N --json
   state,baseRefName,mergedAt` (state=MERGED but baseRefName is an intermediate/closed branch);
   the change lives as a commit on that branch (`git log origin/main..origin/<intermediate>`);
   cherry-pick it onto a fresh main branch (`git cherry-pick -S <sha>` to keep it signed),
   verify it's not a no-op, run the affected tests, then push + open a NEW PR to main.

